{"type":"rich_text_quote","elements":[{"type":"text","text":"I would like to include a symbol of a book with a heart overlayed on top of it, to signify a diary is marked as favourite.

I'm currently achieving this using `Image(systemName: "text.book.closed")` with an overlay and offset modifier of a heart.  What are the pros and cons of using this approach instead of drawing my own custom symbol?

Thanks so much to the team for all the work this year and previously – can't imagine how bland my apps would look without SF Symbols! "},{"type":"emoji","name":"smile","unicode":"1f604"}]}

{"type":"rich_text_quote","elements":[{"type":"text","text":"Hello! I’m making an app with a Tab Bar at the moment, with each tab focusing on a particular overall topic. Inside each Tab Item, there are multiple options inside to change what part of the overall topic is displayed. For example, the Tab Item could be “Goals” and the inside options being “Active” and “Accomplished”

But, I’m not really sure what the best way (HIG-wise) to offer options to have the user select what they would like to see, especially if there are 3 or more options to choose from! 

What would you recommend? Thanks"}]}

{"type":"rich_text_quote","elements":[{"type":"text","text":"When designing rows/cells for lists, how to stop the rows feeling overcrowded with information? 

Also, there are many styles for Tables/Lists. When would you recommend plain list styles vs inset grouped? 

Sorry for all the questions! It’s just so exiting to speak to some of the world’s greatest app designers! "},{"type":"emoji","name":"grin","unicode":"1f601"},{"type":"emoji","name":"grin","unicode":"1f601"}]}

{"type":"rich_text_quote","elements":[{"type":"text","text":"We're a major moving company and are considering a feature that shows the customer's location history during a truck rental. As a rental may span many hours, or even days, and we want to accurately show their driving history, this could be _many_ data points.

I'd like to present this information similar to how you can see your location history during a walk Workout. I tried copying that by creating an MKPolyline over all of the coordinates, and then use a custom MKOverlay for each individual point.

Would that be the most performant way of doing something like this? I found the simulator, and device, lagging a bit when trying to display a dot for about 12,000 data points, and that was just a small subset of data."}]}
